How To Shoot In The 70’s
.
Good Lag Putts are keeping you from shooting lower scores. If it’s breaking 100, 90 or 80 - making strong lag putts will help you level up your golf game. 
.
If you’re a golfer, you’re an athlete. I think if putting like throwing a ball or shooting a free throw. The ball has to get from where you are to where you want it to go. 
.
Something I have tried in my practice that helps with lag putting is looking at the hole/target instead of looking at the ball. Sometimes we get obsessed with the perfect stroke and we forgot about where we need to ball to go. 
.
If you’re struggling with any part of your game, let me know what it is and I’ll try to make a video to help you guys out. 
.
#GolfTip #Golfing #Golftips #Golflessons

Now You Know 😉
.
Easier said than done right? Short irons are just 1 factor that lead to lower scores, but they are a big part of it. 
.
Yes, hitting fairways set you up for better approach shots, but if you’re confident with short irons, you’ll start hitting more greens from the rough. 
.
More balls on the green gives you more birdie looks, and more birdie looks equal more pars. More pars = lower scores.
.
Good luck out there!
.
#GolfTips #GolfLesson #Golfing #Golfer

Here’s how you play 👇🏻
.
You need a foursome, pick a partner. 
.
Let’s say hole 1 is a par four. You and your partner both make a par (4 and 4) your team score would be 44. 
.
Your playing partners make a par and a bogey (4 and 5). This score would be 45. (The lowest score on the hole is the front number, the highest is the back number). 
.
For example, you’re playing $1 a point. 44 vs 45, your playing partners owe you $1 each. 
.
Birdies and eagles are where it gets expensive. 
.
Let’s say on that same par 4, you birdie and your partner makes par (3 and 4) your score is 34. 
.
Your playing partners make a par and a double bogey (4 and 6). 
.
Birdies make the score flip. So instead of 34 vs 46 it’s now 34 vs 64 a difference of 30. $1 a point is $30 per guy just for that hole. 
.
Let’s say both players Birdie (3 and 3) vs the par and double bogey (4 and 6). You reverse their score (now 64) and double the difference. $30 turns to $60 per guy for that hole. 
.
Are you still with me?
.
Eagles reverse double’s just like two birdies. 
.
The ultimate killer is if you and your partner make an eagle and a birdie. Your team is (3 and 4) 34 and your playing partners went par, double (5 and 7). 
.
You would reverse their score, now 75 and then TRIPLE the difference. 34 vs 75 = $41 x 3 = $123 per guy just for that hole lol. 
.
Will you try this game?
.
.
.
.
.
See how this game can get expensive only at $1 / point?

Who’s 💰 You Taking?
. 
Skins is a fun golf game that is typically played with a group of four players. The objective of the game is to win as many “skins” as possible over the course of the round. A skin is essentially a point that is won by a player who has the lowest score on a hole. If two or more players tie for the lowest score on a hole, the skin is carried over to the next hole, increasing its value.
.
At the end of the round, the player with the most skins wins the game. Skins is a fun and exciting way to add a little extra competition to your golf game, and it can be played with both high and low handicappers.
.
Wolf is another popular golf game that is typically played with a group of four players. In Wolf, each player takes turns being the “wolf” on each hole. The wolf is responsible for choosing a partner for the hole, or deciding to go it alone against the other three players.
.
The player who is the wolf for the hole tees off first, and then the other players take turns teeing off in a predetermined order. After all four players have hit their tee shots, the wolf must choose a partner for the hole. The wolf can choose to partner with one of the other players, or go it alone against the other three.
.
The objective of the game is to win as many holes as possible, either individually or as a team with the wolf. At the end of the round, the player with the most points wins the game. 
.
Nassau is a golf gambling game that is typically played with a group of four players. The game is played in three parts: the front nine, the back nine, and the overall round.
.
In each part, players can win points by having the lowest score on each hole, or by winning the overall part. At the end of the round, the player with the most points in each part wins that part, and the player with the most points overall wins the game.
.
Nassau is a fun and competitive way to add a little extra excitement to your golf game, and it can be played with both high and low handicappers.
.

Golf Tips That Actually Work 👇🏻
.
Golf Lessons - no shit 😂
.
Did you know professional golfers take lessons? If the best golfers in the world take lessons, so should you. Take lessons ESPECIALLY if you’re a beginner! And getting tips from your golf friends isn’t a lesson. Find a teaching pro and commit to a package of lessons. 
.
Get a club fitting - 
.
If you got your clubs as a gift or off the rack, I guarantee they are wrong for you. The right head/shaft combo will help you be more consistent, keep the ball in play and shoot lower scores. You can fit every club in your bag including the putter. 
.
Work on your short game - 
.
Putting and chipping should be 90% of your focus if you want to become a better golfer. This is the difference between a high handicap and single digit or scratch golfer. If you can get up and down when you miss a green you will make a lot less double bogeys or worse. Hitting the long ball is cool but it doesn’t guarantee low scores like solid putting and chipping does. 
.
Play with better players - 
.
Take notes on how a better player manages the golf course. Following their golf strategy will get you thinking like a better golfer. 
.
Film your swing - 
.
What you feel and what you see can be 2 totally different things. Watching your golf swing can help identify things you can work on. And if you can’t find those things, go back to step one and take some lessons. A coach will show you what to look for in your golf swing. 
.

Hitting 3/4 wedges helped me hit more greens inside 150 yards and I had way more makable birdie putts.

.
Nothing worse than seeing your divot by the hole put you have a 30 foot putt. 
.
3/4 golf shots also help with those awkward side hill lies. 
.
You’re more likely to make solid contact with that 3/4 swing. 
.
Give it a try!

Here’s how you play 👇🏻
.
You need a foursome, pick a partner. 
.
Let’s say hole 1 is a par four. You and your partner both make a par (4 and 4) your team score would be 44. 
.
Your playing partners make a par and a bogey (4 and 5). This score would be 45. (The lowest score on the hole is the front number, the highest is the back number). 
.
For example, you’re playing $1 a point. 44 vs 45, your playing partners owe you $1 each. 
.
Birdies and eagles are where it gets expensive. 
.
Let’s say on that same par 4, you birdie and your partner makes par (3 and 4) your score is 34. 
.
Your playing partners make a par and a double bogey (4 and 6). 
.
Birdies make the score flip. So instead of 34 vs 46 it’s now 34 vs 64 a difference of 30. $1 a point is $30 per guy just for that hole. 
.
Let’s say both players Birdie (3 and 3) vs the par and double bogey (4 and 6). You reverse their score (now 64) and double the difference. $30 turns to $60 per guy for that hole. 
.
Are you still with me?
.
Eagles reverse double’s just like two birdies. 
.
The ultimate killer is if you and your partner make an eagle and a birdie. Your team is (3 and 4) 34 and your playing partners went par, double (5 and 7). 
.
You would reverse their score, now 75 and then TRIPLE the difference. 34 vs 75 = $41 x 3 = $123 per guy just for that hole lol. 
.
Will you try this game?

.
.
See how this game can get expensive only at $1 / point?
